              *****************LINUX COMMANDS*******************************

VM(Virtual Machine) should be present in any location and to access it we can do it from anywhere — we just need internet.

To start use “sudo -su -” to switch to root user.
Everything will be inside the root.


************Commands****************************

----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
1. ls – List Files & Directory
File / Directory:
1. Files -Just Files in a system 
2. Directory → It is nothing but a folder in Windows in your drive.
Examples: .doc,.excel, .powerpoint
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
2. ls -l → long listing format
----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
3. mkdir → To create the directory
Example:   mkdir dirname
  mk → make
  dir → directory
  dirname → any name
----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
4. cd → To go inside directory
Example: cd directoryname
----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
5. To check which directory we are present use “pwd”.
Example: pwd
Output: /root/username
----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
6. To go to root just use cd / → we go inside root.
----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
7. To directly go into a specific directory
Example:
cd /dirpath/filename
----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
8. touch → To create an empty file
Example: touch filename
----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
9. ll → To verify directory & file in Linux
Directory name will be bold &
file is normal.
----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
10.  pwd → Prints the current directory that you’re present
----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
11. rmdir → To remove/delete directory that is empty
Example: rmdir dirname
Note: Only works on empty directory. Won’t work on directory which has any file in it.
----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
12. rm → To remove/delete the file inside directory
Example: rm filename
----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
13. cp → To copy the file from one directory to other directory
Example: cp file path space directory name (path)
Example given: cp /root/Cricket/Team1 /root/Football/
----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
14. mv → To move the file from one directory to other directory
mv → Move the file

Note : The file will be deleted from one directory and moved to the directory which is selected.

Example: mv /Imad/demo  /Faizan/
(directory name → file name → directory name)
Example given (Laptop): mv /root/Imad/Demo /root/Faizan/
----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
15. To move from one directory to other fast we use: cd /dirname/
To go back from one directory to another you can use: cd ..
----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
16. cat → Used when you read the file
Example:cat filename
Note :It works only on files, not on directories.
----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
17. To verify which is directory & which is file we use “ll” command.
If at the start we have d → it is a directory
If there is no d → then it is a file.
----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
18.  vi → It is used to write content in the empty file
Example:
vi filename
Then press i (insert mode)
Then write the content
After that to save the file press:
Esc button → then type :wq! → Enter.
----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
19. find → To find any content without opening the file
Example: find -filename (or find “word”)
If you are not in the directory then give full path after find.
----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
                           *****************8 End Of Basic Linux Command ***************************************











